3.3 Technology as a Mediator

Technology is a double‑edged sword. Social media algorithms amplify tribalism; echo chambers harden biases; disinformation spreads faster than truth. But the same technologies can be redesigned or repurposed for convergence. This section focuses on AI for conflict resolution, fair resource allocation, and communication—the positive edge.

AI‑powered peacebuilding has moved from science fiction to operational reality. The Peace Navigator, launched by Principles for Peace in December 2025, is an AI‑driven decision‑support platform that combines 21 years of data from 56 conflict‑affected countries, over 50,000 webpages, and 29,000 documents. It features a chat interface that provides real‑time situational awareness, scenario simulation, and strategic guidance for mediators, diplomats, and local peacebuilders. Early field tests in the Sahel and the Caucasus showed that users could access relevant case studies (what worked in similar contexts) within seconds, avoiding the “reinventing the wheel” problem that plagues peace processes. The platform also flags potential blind spots—e.g., “You have not consulted women’s groups” or “This agreement failed twice before under similar conditions.”

A framework for AI‑assisted peace dialogues was proposed by Wählisch and Kufus (September 2025) in Data & Policy. They argue for context‑sensitive taxonomy of digital deliberation tools, distinguishing between AI‑facilitated (algorithm suggests conversation starters), AI‑mediated (algorithm filters hate speech and summarises views), and AI‑augmented (algorithm generates option portfolios for negotiators). They emphasise hybrid models: AI handles scale, data processing, and pattern recognition; humans provide empathy, creativity, and legitimacy. Pilot projects in Colombia (land restitution dialogues) and Northern Ireland (community safety forums) reduced meeting time by 40% while increasing perceived fairness.

The Centre for Humanitarian Dialogue (CMI, October 2025) identified three areas where AI enhances peacebuilding: (a) better conflict analysis (natural language processing of local media and social media to detect rising tensions), (b) better listening (AI‑powered sentiment analysis of citizen submissions in peace processes, scaling from hundreds to millions of voices), and (c) better decision‑making (scenario modelling and game theory to predict consequences of different ceasefire terms). These tools are not replacing human judgement but augmenting it, reducing the cognitive biases (overconfidence, groupthink, availability heuristic) that plague manual negotiation.

Social platforms for collaboration, not polarisation. A 2025 experimental study redesigned a social media feed to prioritise “bridging content”—posts that were liked by both liberals and conservatives, or by users from different ethnic groups. The algorithm reduced polarisation metrics (affective polarisation, outgroup animosity) by 25% within two weeks, without reducing engagement. Similarly, the platform ListenFirst (launched 2025) uses structured deliberation protocols (like the “Common Ground” algorithm) to match users with different views for one‑on‑one conversations, with AI providing real‑time prompts (“Try rephrasing that as a question”) and post‑conversation reflection questions. Early data show that 70% of users report increased respect for the other side.

Fair resource allocation is another AI application. Computational social choice algorithms can divide resources (e.g., disaster relief, refugee quotas, carbon emission permits) in ways that are provably fair, transparent, and resistant to strategic manipulation. The 2025 “collaboration vouchers” policy (Open Research Newcastle) uses a simple algorithm to allocate small monetary incentives to individuals who complete cross‑group collaborative tasks (e.g., a group project with someone from a different neighbourhood). The cost is trivial (e.g., $50 per person), but the effect on trust and future cooperation is significant. AI can optimise matching—pairing people who are most likely to benefit from contact—while avoiding manipulative “nudging.”

Ethical safeguards are non‑negotiable. AI for convergence must be: (a) transparent (users can inspect how decisions are made), (b) accountable (humans retain final authority), (c) privacy‑preserving (no surveillance of individuals), and (d) culturally adaptive (not imposing Western norms). The 2025 UNESCO Recommendation on the Ethics of AI provides a framework that this thesis endorses.

